{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643832"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:58:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:58:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18015"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18015"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[1,0,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78470"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10729"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63832"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7292"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24974"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78470"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe trapezius is a large, triangular muscle extending from the skull to the lower thoracic vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following actions is provided by the trapezius muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevation of the scapula","Flexion of the elbow","Internal rotation of the humerus","Rotation of the forearm","Extension of the wrist"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevation of the scapula\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the primary actions of the trapezius muscle. The trapezius is a large muscle that extends from the occipital bone to the lower thoracic vertebrae and laterally to the spine of the scapula. It is responsible for moving, rotating, and stabilising the scapula and extending the neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexion of the elbow\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily performed by the biceps brachii and brachialis muscles, not the trapezius\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal rotation of the humerus\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by the subscapularis, latissimus dorsi, and teres major muscles, not the trapezius\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotation of the forearm\u003C/strong\u003E involves the pronator teres and supinator muscles, not the trapezius\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtension of the wrist\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by the extensor carpi radialis longus, extensor carpi radialis brevis, and extensor carpi ulnaris muscles, not the trapezius\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The trapezius muscle is responsible for multiple actions including elevation, retraction, and rotation of the scapula.","The trapezius also assists in extending and laterally flexing the neck.","The trapezius has no direct action on the elbow, shoulder joint, or forearm movements."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63832"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18015"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63832"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T21:19:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T00:02:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10729"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78470"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms"